comment_text_display:
​​@@EngLit123out of the box: kind of. But after the update and about 3 days later, it's not really noticeable. You notice some minor banding, but it's not noticeable in my opinion. It's like the G4 basically (which was my previous TV).

Also, the TV is so bright, you'll definitely have to lower the brightness: this improves the banding issues significantly (from my experience).

However, I'd say go into a store and actually see it before buying. That's what I did. Tested YouTube, 4K HDR10 footage etc. Hope this helps.

comment_text_display:
You should try and disable HDR on whatever streaming service or games console youre using if possible. Since the TV has no Local Dimming it will probably look objectively better it you just watch in SDR and turn the backlight up.

Even with the VA panel in the 43 and 50" helping with contrast having the backlight set to max for HDR will increase the black level way beyond what it would be with SDR.

Just a suggestion to try, if you're enjoying the TV as is just continue doing that and ignore me ha.
comment_text_original:
You should try and disable HDR on whatever streaming service or games console youre using if possible. Since the TV has no Local Dimming it will probably look objectively better it you just watch in SDR and turn the backlight up.

Even with the VA panel in the 43 and 50" helping with contrast having the backlight set to max for HDR will increase the black level way beyond what it would be with SDR.

Just a suggestion to try, if you're enjoying the TV as is just continue doing that and ignore me ha.

I genuinely appreciate the effort you put into your content, but I have to point out something important. Please avoid recommending products solely based on listed specifications or what’s shown on e-commerce websites. Many times, the specs provided online are either misleading or flat-out incorrect, and relying on them without proper hands-on testing can misguide your audience.
If you're reviewing a product, it needs to be based on real-world use — not just reading off a spec sheet or promotional page. Your viewers trust your opinion, and that trust can be damaged if the products don’t live up to your recommendations in actual usage.
Please take this as constructive feedback: moving forward, only recommend products you’ve personally tested and can vouch for through actual experience. Your credibility depends on it, and your audience deserves nothing less.

comment_text_display:
​​@@TheGrapevineIndiaThere are TVs and there are great TVs. Just so there are reviewers and there are great reviewers. In my assessment there are two reviewers who are good and unbiased - The Grapevine and VMOne ( Vineet Malhotra). Since both of you have the potential to be the best in the game, your followers, including me, would be unduly harsh in our comments.

Coming to the point, I agree with you but with caveats. All these features which you mentioned ( Color Gamut, HDR 10+, Refresh rate, MEMC, Sound Output, etc.,etc.) are important, no doubt. But they are important only if the TV still works after 3-4 years. And so in my opinion it is the build quality and durability of the TV that is of utmost importance and which nobody reviews.

What is build quality in a TV ?? It is the quality of components that go into it - the panel( who made it LG or TCL or some cheap manufacturer), what is the grade of the panel, who manufactured the T- Con board, what is the quality of the capacitors used ( Japanese or good Chinese like TCL or cheap generic Chinese manufacturers), etc. Furthermore, what is the pedigree of the Company. The best are of course Sony, LG and Samsung whose TVs last for 10+ years. Then, there is high quality Chinese companies who have invested in TV R&D and whose TVs last 7-8 years. And then there are marketing motor mouths like Hisense, Haier, Nokia etc. who survive only on high decibel marketing. Lastly there are the bottom feeder aggregators who buy the cheapest components, assemble it here without any sort of QC or QA.

There are details like ventilation ( heat is a big enemy) plastic or metal back panel (metal dissipitates heat fast) and so on.
An indicator of the seriousness of the companies would be the periodicity and quality of updates provided by the Company. These could be OS updates or other updates. While the high quality manufacturers like Sony are on Android 12 and 13, the cheap trash like Hisense, Haier, Xiaomi are still on Android 9 or 10. Lastly one should also review the After Sales Service which is excellent for Sony, Samsung and LG, quite good for TCL and virtually non-existent for other brands.

comment_text_original:
​​@@TheGrapevineIndiaThere are TVs and there are great TVs. Just so there are reviewers and there are great reviewers. In my assessment there are two reviewers who are good and unbiased - The Grapevine and VMOne ( Vineet Malhotra). Since both of you have the potential to be the best in the game, your followers, including me, would be unduly harsh in our comments.

Coming to the point, I agree with you but with caveats.  All these features which you mentioned  ( Color Gamut, HDR 10+, Refresh rate, MEMC, Sound Output, etc.,etc.) are important, no doubt. But they are important only if the TV still works after 3-4 years. And so in my opinion it is the build quality and durability of the TV that is of utmost importance and which nobody reviews.

What is build quality in a TV ?? It is the quality of components that go into it - the panel( who made it LG or TCL or some cheap manufacturer), what is the grade of the panel, who manufactured the T- Con board, what is the quality of the capacitors used ( Japanese or good Chinese like TCL or cheap generic Chinese manufacturers), etc.  Furthermore, what is the pedigree of the Company. The best are of course Sony, LG and Samsung whose TVs last for 10+ years. Then, there is high quality Chinese companies who have invested in TV R&D and whose TVs last 7-8 years. And then there are marketing motor mouths like Hisense, Haier, Nokia etc. who survive only on high decibel marketing. Lastly there are the bottom feeder aggregators who buy the cheapest components, assemble it here without any sort of QC or QA. 

There are details like ventilation ( heat is a big enemy) plastic or metal back panel (metal dissipitates heat fast) and so on.
An indicator of the seriousness of the companies would be the periodicity and quality of updates provided by the Company. These could be OS updates or other updates. While the high quality manufacturers like Sony are on Android 12 and 13, the cheap trash like Hisense, Haier, Xiaomi are still on Android 9 or 10.  Lastly one should also review the After Sales Service which is excellent for Sony, Samsung and LG, quite good for TCL and virtually non-existent for other brands.

Sorry to be harsh. But you could be one of the best reviewer if only you stop talking about the superficial which can be gleaned from the internet and get to brass tacks.

comment_text_display:
Some points that need to be noted:
1. Of the premium segments, Mini-LEDs offer higher brightness and color volume whereas OLEDs offer better viewing angles and contrast.
2. OLEDs tend to suffer a higher rate of Burn-In in hotter areas (more than 40 degrees), so if you are planning to buy a premium TV, and you are from such an area and your living room does not have AC, go for a Mini-LED TV instead of OLED.
3. If your budget do not allow for you to get a higher tier version of latest model, go for last year model of that tier, like if Samsung QN90F (2025) is out of budget, opt for QN90D (2024). Yes QN85F (2025) has some features that looks on paper better than QN90D, but 90 series is a higher tier than 85, as such will have more local-dimming zones and better HDR management (in some cases) and so on, which results in better experience. This cannot be followed when choosing mid-range TVs, as the upgrades year-on-year is greater in those segments.
4. Hisense Q series, TCL C series are extremely good deals which offer Samsung Mini-LED QLED and Sony Mini-LED levels of performance at lower price bracket. But their other ranges are things to be debated.

comment_text_display:
I genuinely appreciate the effort you put into your content, but I have to point out something important. Please avoid recommending products solely based on listed specifications or what’s shown on e-commerce websites. Many times, the specs provided online are either misleading or flat-out incorrect, and relying on them without proper hands-on testing can misguide your audience.
If you're reviewing a product, it needs to be based on real-world use — not just reading off a spec sheet or promotional page. Your viewers trust your opinion, and that trust can be damaged if the products don’t live up to your recommendations in actual usage.
Please take this as constructive feedback: moving forward, only recommend products you’ve personally tested and can vouch for through actual experience. Your credibility depends on it, and your audience deserves nothing less.
